> Patrick learned how to make this dish whilst filming in the beautiful coastal town of Catania and has decided to recreate it with a few of his own flavours. Italians are fiercely protective of their recipes so, for his sake, let's keep this one under our hats!

Pre-heat your #oven{} to 220 degrees. Slice the @aubergine{2} in half lengthways and then slice each half into five strips. Chop the aubergine into 2cm cubes, finely chop the @celery stick{1} and peel and chop @garlic clove{1} of garlic. Remove the core from the @red pepper{1} and @green pepper{1} and chop into little bite-sized chunks.

In a #bowl{}, coat the aubergine and peppers in @olive oil{2%tbsp}. Spread evenly on a #baking tray{} and roast on the top shelf of your oven. Cook for ~{20%minutes} or until a little crispy around the edges.

Heat @olive oil{2%tbsp} in a large #non-stick frying pan{} on medium heat. Once hot, add in the celery and @garlic{2%cloves} with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}. Whilst this cooks, slice open the @Tuscan pork sausage{1}, discard the skin and add the meat to the pan. Break it up and cook for ~{5%minutes}.

Tip in the @chopped tomatoes{2} and then refill one tin a quarter with water. Swill the water around and add this into the sauce. Add @salt{1/2%tsp}, @sugar{2%tsp}(if you have some), the @olives{4} and the @white wine vinegar{2%tbsp}. Leave to simmer and thicken up for ~{10-15%minutes}.

Once your vegetables have roasted, remove from the oven. Turn your #grill{} to high. Add your roasted vegetables into the #pan{} and stir.

Cut the @ciabatta{2} in half and toast under your grill. Once toasted, cut the remaining cloves of garlic in half. Rub the half cloves of garlic across the top of each ciabatta. Drizzle over a little @olive oil{little} and a @salt{pinch}.

Once your caponata has thickened up, serve into warm #bowls{}. It can be eaten with cutlery or by using the ciabatta as a small edible shovel!